{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4de79ea9-9578-465f-be78-402b2907cd0c","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a trace (30 seconds example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet-trace` can't be installed (minimal image), use **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar instead — it exposes a REST API for on-demand trace collection.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` over manual stop to avoid forgetting a running trace.\n- Copy the file out with: `kubectl cp <pod>:trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"123f8191-5bd5-4945-8c2c-6a1589ea7378","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":367,"requestId":"C904:A3554:1D2B474:20501DB:6A0525AD"},"id":"b21339b9-ede0-498f-8b59-24f3d04c009a","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:30:30.684Z","parentId":"854394b5-a8bb-495b-8eaa-bb7b5df09031"}
